Erik

Subtitle: Co-Founder, Adalysis: PPC Recommendation Software for Google Ads & Microsoft Ads. Author & Speaker.
comments:
There are a few ways to think about this. 

1. Adding adjustments only changes the associated list. If true, then campaigns would not see more conversions (or lower CPAs if above target). We often see more efficient campaigns with audience adjustments.

2. It adjusts the impression share by audience. If true, then we are giving the system better signals for targeting - and when systems get more data - they do a better job.

3. Audience adjustments aren't used (I still hear this). If this were true, then we wouldn't ever see data changes with adjustments - I think we can rule this out.

We also know that smart bidding makes a lot of dumb decisions. For instance, they don't use n-grams to be better at bidding (https://adalysis.com/blog/how-to-steer-the-machine-with-negative-keywords/). And that's why we give the machine signals with negative keywords. 

They don't learn about 'matching queries' very well. I.e. "average cost of XYZ" is the EXACT same as "XYZ Quote" in Google's eye even though the first is 3x average CPA of the second.

The truth with audiences probably lies between 1 & 2. We're hand feeding the system better signals to use (of which is probably missed some itself) and, therefore, making it more efficient.

Subtitle: Founder, The Brand Audit | Ex-LinkedIn | LinkedIn Top Voice
comments:
Ryan, while I’m a huge advocate of the AI revolution and think it can be used for basic copywriting or refining one’s content, I do not believe current AI models are sophistated enough to create meaningful Executive thought leadership wholly. 

A few reasons for why:

It lacks personal experience. 
??Thought leadership relies on personal insights, stories, anecdotes and in-depth industry knowledge. This is often very nuanced and hard to fake.

Inability to Stay Relevant 
??The best thought leadership is often reactions or commentary on current events. Most AI models have a delay and are not able to tap in the most current trends and news developments. 

Risk of Bias and Not Including Diverse perspectives 
??We all know AI models are faulty in this area. Even if it’s trained on your own voice it may not overcome these. 

Human Emotion & Empathy
??Engaging thought leadership requires the writer to be highly empathetic and tap into the emotions of the audience. Humans can adapt their message for context but AI had difficulty doing this.

comments:
Wow - impressive! 
But I’m also curious - as the intended author, what do YOU think? Did it capture all the points you would have touched on yourself, and do you agree with the perspectives it did bring forth? How close do you think it is to your natural writing style? 

I think these tools are really wonderful for creating a base of content. But I also think it’s important to do the creative/objective thinking BEFORE using them, in order to capture original thought before being served up with the generated content - and then meld them together. 

Otherwise we’ll end up with a sea of sameness echoing across the ether under countless bylines, with no actual leadership contained in the thoughts.

comments: Not having read the article due to the payall, I wouldn't agree with that formula, though this can quickly degenerate into semantics. Empathy is putting yourself in someone else's position, actually feeling what you imagine they are feeling. Since it is imaginative, it is notoriously biased toward people you identify with. Empathy is not particularly helpful in my view. Two people in the ditch kind of thing. Compassion, on the other hand is active helping. It does not require empathy other than perhaps the cognitive kind, only the desire to diminish suffering. I like Paul Bloom's Against Empathy on this topic. FWIW.

Subtitle: Life on a burning platform
comments: Compassion and empathy are quite different. Empathy is an emotional identification with a person‘s suffering. And, as such, has various foibles that have been recently pointed out (such as an increased tendency to partisanship). Compassion is a dispassionate, rational response — to recognise suffering wherever it happens, without taking sides. An empathetic person will side with a victim and demonise a victimiser, whether the situation is black-and-white or shades of grey. A compassionate person will acknowledge the suffering in both victim and victimiser.

comments:
Work trauma is such an important issue to highlight. It can have potentially devasting consequences on not only your career but your life outside of work. 

We spend c.1,795 hours a year at work. A year has 8,760 hours. That means we spend 20% of our entire year at work.

Don't give your employees one more thing to worry about. Especially in today's climate. 

The idea that as they're on their way to work, they're preparing to go into battle with their colleagues or managers is absurd.

It's so disheartening to acknowledge that some managers misuse their position, resorting to tactics like bullying, gaslighting, or mistreatment of their employees. For what? To feel powerful? To avoid accountability or blame? 

What we truly need are leaders who can foster a workplace culture that is safe, supportive, and inclusive. 
 
As an employee, remember to...

1. Set Boundaries
2. Seek Support
3. Advocate for Yourself

If that fails, contact a recruiter who can support you through your search for a more positive work environment. ??

Subtitle: Learning & Engagement | Leading with Strategy, Empathy & Intentional Development
comments: Rachael Turquand it sure is! This is why I firmly believe that any manager training that doesn’t also root into “personal transformation” & self-reflection / trauma-informed practices (my dream!) misses the mark. So many times these behaviors aren’t always / exclusively a conscious choice - unless we’re talking true narcissism -then MAYBE. They’re (mal)adaptive strategies to achieve a desired result (self-esteem, power, control, etc.) This in NO way makes it better, acceptable, or removes accountability, quite the contrary. It just means that we can’t separate ourselves or our behaviors from work in the way we want or in the way capitalism demands of us. We show up at work and in work relationships often times as we would in “real life” relationships. I’d honestly argue that work conditions can create more problematic behaviors, if the conditions are right. Just as work can “trigger” us more than other things might. The managers who positively impacted my mental health were folks who had “done the work.” They had high self-awareness, genuine capacity for empathy, along with practical teachable skills needed to manage.

comments:
"Excuses will lead to unhappiness, period." It's like saying, "If you keep blaming your tools, you'll never build the house." But let's dig a bit deeper. Sure, on the surface, excuses feel like a comfy bed you never want to leave. They're those "But I can't because..." moments that save us from facing our fears or stepping out of our comfort zones. But here’s the catch: that bed of excuses? It's actually a bed of nails in disguise. The more you lie in it, the more it hurts.
Imagine a world where nobody made excuses. Sounds pretty intense, right? Like, suddenly everyone's living their best life, chasing dreams without a single "I can't" in sight. But let's be real: making excuses is part of being human. The key isn't to never make excuses; it's to not let them hold the reins.
Flipping the script, what if every excuse was a signal, not a stop sign? Like, "I don’t have time" means "I need to prioritize." It's about turning excuses into questions: "What's really stopping me?"
So, yeah, lounging in Excuse City might seem chill at first, but it's a one-way ticket to Regretsville. The trick is recognizing those excuses for what they are: little hurdles your brain puts up because it's scared of falling.

comments:
It's super important to understand the difference between an excuse and a reason, right? We've all got things in our lives that are hard, stuff that really challenges us. But the key is in how we handle those challenges. When you start making excuses, you're giving away your power to change things. You're saying, "I can't do anything about this," and that mindset is a straight path to feeling stuck and unhappy.
I'm not saying you ignore the real reasons that might be holding you back. It's essential to be aware of what's happening inside your head and in your life. Being real with yourself about your scenario is the first step towards making positive changes. It’s about owning your situation, not letting it own you.

Mindset is everything. It's not about brushing off the truth of what you're dealing with; it's about saying, "Okay, this is my reality, now how am I going to rise above it?" It's about finding that grit and determination to push through the tough stuff and come out stronger on the other side. And remember, it's okay to ask for help when you need it. There's strength in that, too.

Great book
Key aspects of the book include:

- **Lincoln's Political Strategy**: Goodwin delves into how Lincoln was able to bring his competitors together, creating a cabinet that was unmatched in its abilities. Despite their differences, Lincoln managed to direct their talents toward a common goal, demonstrating his exceptional skills in persuasion and empathy.

- **In-depth Character Studies**: The book offers detailed portraits of the key figures in Lincoln's cabinet, including William H. Seward, Salmon P. Chase, Edwin M. Stanton, and Edward Bates. These profiles provide insights into their personal ambitions, political beliefs.

"Team of Rivals" has been praised for its detailed research, engaging writing style, and its portrayal of Lincoln as a leader capable of reconciling conflicting personalities and viewpoints for the greater good. The book was awarded the Lincoln Prize and the inaugural Book Prize for American History from the New-York Historical Society. It also served as a partial basis for the 2012 film "Lincoln," directed by Steven Spielberg.

Goodwin's work is not just a biography of Lincoln but a study in leadership, political strategy, and human nature, offering valuable lessons that are still relevant today.

comments:
Signs that a marketer may be using fear in their content:

1. Exaggerated Language: They use hyperbolic language to emphasize potential dangers or consequences, making the situation seem more dire than it actually is.

2. Negative Imagery: They utilize images or visuals that evoke fear, such as scenes of danger, accidents, or ominous symbols.

3. Creating Urgency: They employ phrases like "limited time offer" or "act now before it's too late" to instill a sense of urgency and fear of missing out (FOMO).

4. Highlighting Risks: They focus on potential risks or dangers associated with not using their product or service, playing on people's fears of negative outcomes.

5. Emphasizing Loss: They highlight what customers stand to lose if they don't take action, rather than focusing on the benefits of their product or service.

comments:
6. Using Statistics: They cite statistics or data to illustrate the magnitude of a problem, amplifying fear by presenting it as widespread or inevitable.

7. Creating Scenarios: They paint vivid scenarios of worst-case outcomes to illustrate the consequences of not taking action, tapping into people's fear of uncertainty.

8. Fear of Missing Out (FOMO): They play on people's fear of missing out on opportunities or experiences by suggesting that their product or service is essential for staying ahead or keeping up with others.

9. Social Proof through Fear: They use testimonials or stories that emphasize how others suffered negative consequences due to not using their product or service, fostering fear of similar outcomes.

10. Emotional Manipulation: They manipulate emotions such as anxiety, insecurity, or vulnerability to persuade people to take action, often by presenting their product or service as the solution to their fears.

Recognizing these tactics can help consumers make more informed decisions and discern when marketers are using fear-based strategies to influence behavior.

As mentioned, AI has the potential to transform the way we live and work, from healthcare to logistics to finance. It's already being used in many industries to automate routine tasks, improve decision-making, and enhance customer experiences.

However, it's important to remember that AI is not a universal solution. It's just a tool that we can use to augment our own abilities and make our lives easier. And while it's true that AI has the potential to replace certain jobs, it also has the potential to create new jobs and opportunities.

At the end of the day, the impact of AI will depend on how we choose to use it. We can either use it to replace human workers and reduce costs, or we can use it to enhance human potential and create new opportunities. It's up to us to decide how we want to shape the future of AI.

Thanks for sharing your thoughts, and I look forward to seeing how AI continues to evolve and impact our world.

A specific time can fix that.

"I'll give you an update by Wednesday at 5pm," is much more specific.

comments: This happened and it drove me nuts! I really had a hard time seeing no acknowledgment email sent to our customers when issues came in. Mind-reading machines are here: is it time to worry? ?Nature News Explainer article 2023?
This technology still needs to achieve true mind-reading. Policymakers must ensure that brain-computer interface technology, specifically invasive BCIs, is not abused!
We will never forget the most humiliating Nobel Prize in Medicine in human history: the Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine of 1949 for the "discovery of the therapeutic value of leucotomy in certain psychoses," This kind of "lobotomy surgery" turns madmen into fools and causes enormous harm to the fields of human medicine and neuroscience.
The prerequisite for using the brain's motor cortex signals to control external devices is an actual mind-reading machine. So far, human neuroscience can only describe simple brain states such as sleep and resting-task states with eyes open and closed. A little human thought hinting from fMRI and EEG signals is still far from true mind-reading. Many diseases should rely more on humans' self-healing capabilities than invasive BCIs.

Subtitle: Transforming corporate high-performers through human design coaching from surviving to thriving | re-discover your purpose | ICF Certififed Coach | Life Coach | #youaremorethancapable
comments:
I've been struggling with it a little bit too.

A couple important points...

First some of us struggle with instant gratification in terms of building business because we are drowning.

We are living in a country and in a world that in many ways has failed to provide us with a decent life.

We care so much more about corporate profits than other humans and their well being and it's so incredibly backwards.

So unfortunately, some people did need the business to skyrocket, they needed the post to go viral yesterday.  And everyday that it doesn't may be too late.

Then there is the concept of expectations.  We are shooting ourselves in the foot by making goals for things like follower count or bigger business results in the short term.

These should be set on a yearly basis or more.

Thinking we can set short term goals creates an expectation in our mind that we for sure will create that "baseline" and then we just set ourselves up for failure.

Subtitle: SmarTech Solutions Beyond the Hype - Strategisch, Intelligent, Messbar
comments:
The one thing I don’t get… why do parents push their kids so hard to have perfect grades and be the best at sports.

You don’t need your kid to get intro Harvard.

There’s nothing wrong with Harvard, and I couldn’t have gotten in even if I applied, but going to one of these schools doesn’t guarantee financial success.

It guarantees financial debt.

I know people who went to Ivy League schools and people who didn’t. And I have rich friends on both sides.

Neither guarantees success.

Nor does being able to do math equations in your head or having the perfect golf swing.

Most of the people who I know that are financially successful did well because:

1. They are resilient and don’t ever quit.
2. They are risk takers and will put everything on the line to accomplish their dreams.
3. They learn from their mistakes. They may not be the smartest but they know if they don’t make the same mistakes over and over again they are more likely to succeed.
4. They go after big ideas. The riches aren’t in the niches, they are in big markets.
5. They are super creative problem solvers. You’ll never have enough time or money, you have to think outside the box.

If you want to push your kids go for it. But it doesn’t guarantee financial success.

Subtitle: Partnering with agency founders (>$1.5M ARR) to 4x sales, marketing & retention results | $80M+ in ARR generated for B2B companies
comments:
Neil - love this man, so true.

There's so much energy, time, stress & effort put in by parents to do this, but doesn't have to be the case.

Want to do it? Sure, go for it.

Will it give your children guaranteed success - probably not.

Here's what I feel we as parents need to focus on more:

1/ Cultivate entrepreneurship (which is now more important than ever)

2/ Teach them to "give" selflessly (help others, without expecting anything in return)

3/ Grit - it's ok to fail, get up, keep going.

Like you said - I've seen success on both sides of the fence too, but those that succeeded had the above engrained in them.

We put a lot of pressure on ourselves as parents - but just know, eventually, it'll work out ok :)
